The paper deals with the problem of finding (approximate) nearest neighbors in high-dimensional spaces, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has applications in various fields such as computer vision and machine learning. The paper uses graph-based approaches to solve this problem and analyzes the time-space trade-offs of these approaches. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), followed by cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also mentions applications in computer vision (cs.CV) and lattice sieving (cs.DM), which are less likely but still relevant categories.
